# .dockerignore — what NOT to send to the Docker build context.
#
# This is the image-based analogue of Lab 04's .deployignore. The build context
# is everything Docker tars up and hands to the daemon before running the
# Dockerfile. Anything matched here:
#   - never enters the build context (faster builds, smaller upload)
#   - can never be COPY-ed into the image by accident (smaller, cleaner image)
#   - keeps secrets and lab tooling out of a published artifact
#
# Format: same glob rules as .gitignore. One pattern per line.
#
# Rule of thumb: the only things the Dockerfile actually COPYs are projects/,
# services/config/, services/modules.json, and third-party-modules/. Everything
# else is noise in the build context — exclude it.

# Version control + git internals
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# Secrets and local env (NEVER bake these into a published image)
.env
.env.example

# Lab teaching material — has nothing to do with the gateway runtime
README.md
LICENSE
docs/
exercises/
instructor-notes/
scripts/
slides/
tests/

# CI / compose / test-only files
.github/
docker-compose.yaml
Dockerfile
.dockerignore

# Database bootstrap (runs in the TimescaleDB sidecar, not the gateway image)
db-init/

# Per-instance identity — belongs to ONE gateway, never bake it into a shared
# image. Same rule as Lab 04's .deployignore, excluded BY NAME:
#   - config/local + config/resources/local: UUID, gateway-network keystore,
#     OPC-UA keystores, machine-local system props
#   - the INTERNAL identity trio: users.json carries the LOCAL gateway's admin
#     password hash; baking it ships your admin login to every gateway running
#     the image — instant lockout. Identity resources you add yourself
#     (database/AD user sources, SAML/OIDC providers) hold no password data
#     and ARE baked like any other config.
# These dirs are gitignored too; the patterns here protect local builds
# (scripts/build-image.sh) run from a working tree where the local gateway
# has written them.
services/config/local/
services/config/resources/local/
services/config/resources/core/ignition/user-source/default/
services/config/resources/core/ignition/user-source/opcua-module/
services/config/resources/core/ignition/identity-provider/default/

# security-properties points systemAuthProfile at `default` — the internal
# user source excluded above. An image-based gateway re-commissions on every
# container recreate, and commissioning that finds a security-properties file
# WITHOUT its matching user source plays safe: it creates a temp_N identity
# and rewrites the file to point at it. Keep the file out of the image and
# commissioning instead creates the clean `default` identity from the
# container's GATEWAY_ADMIN_* env vars — the same end state Lab 04's test/production
# gateways reach. (A production image CAN bake it when systemAuthProfile
# names a deployable user source, e.g. an AD/database one, instead of the
# gateway-owned internal one.)
services/config/resources/core/ignition/security-properties/

# Per-instance keystores and secrets. The actual keystore files are gitignored
# (regenerated per gateway), so they're never in the build context — these
# patterns are belt-and-suspenders so a stray keystore can't get baked into a
# shared image.
**/keystore/*.jks
**/keystore/*.p12
**/*.idb

# Ignition operational state + content-addressed blob noise — never bake these
**/.resources/
**/migration-log-*.md
**/data/db/
**/data/users.idb
**/data/temp/
**/data/logs/
**/data/.metadata/

# OS / editor noise
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
